      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions used for validation are documented and sufficiently representative of the COU operating envelope including flow rate and rotational speed ranges.",
      "rationale": "Experimental benchmark data from the FDA critical path initiative covers the 5 flow-speed combinations specified in the COU. Inlet boundary conditions, fluid properties (bovine blood at 37°C), and pump geometry are documented and traceable to the published FDA dataset."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison between CFD-predicted and experimentally measured hemolysis index (RH) demonstrates agreement within defined tolerance bands across all 5 operating points.",
      "rationale": "CFD predictions of normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) agreed with experimental measurements within 15% at 4 of 5 operating points; the fifth point showed 19% deviation attributed to secondary flow instabilities at low flow rate. Overall RH < 1 criterion satisfied, supporting the acceptance decision."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The quantities of interest (NIH, RH) are directly relevant to the clinical decision being made and are sensitive to the geometric variations under investigation.",
      "rationale": "NIH and RH are the standard quantities of interest for hemolysis assessment in blood-contacting devices per ASTM F1841. Sensitivity analysis confirmed that RH is responsive to impeller clearance variations of ±0.1 mm, directly supporting the tolerance decision."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
